@course

id: book:a-brief-history-of-time-cnwo
title: A Brief History of Time
author: Stephen Hawking
description: How a few patient observations of distant light told us the universe had a beginning.
color: #1e293b
genres: science, physics
relevant_for: curious readers, students, anyone

@segment
The Expanding Universe
EU

@package
The Light That Gave It Away
Free

@text
For most of recorded history, almost everyone assumed the universe was eternal.
Not unchanging. Stars were born and died.
But the universe as a whole was thought to have always been there.
This was the default assumption of almost every physicist, including Einstein.
The evidence that proved it wrong came from careful measurements of distant light.

@text
In the 1920s, around the time radio was becoming common, an astronomer photographed faint smudges of light.
His name was Edwin Hubble.
Nobody knew if these smudges were clouds inside our galaxy or separate galaxies far away.
Hubble spread the light from each smudge into its component colors using a spectrograph.
He noticed the colors were shifted toward red.
The farther away a galaxy was, the more its colors had shifted.
He plotted the data, and the pattern was almost a straight line.

@text
To understand the redshift, think about what sound does when its source moves.
A siren sounds higher when an ambulance approaches, and lower once it passes.
Light does the same. A source moving away shifts its colors toward red.
Redshift means "the source is moving away."
Redshift that grows with distance means "farther sources are moving away faster."
Physicists already had equations that predicted exactly this.

@text
The straight line in Hubble's plot meant the universe is expanding.
If every galaxy is moving away from every other galaxy, then in the past they were all closer.
Further back, the universe was smaller, denser, and hotter.
Follow the expansion backward far enough and everything was packed into a space smaller than a room.
Further back still, smaller than an atom.
This is not a comparison. It is what the data says.
The universe had a beginning.

@question
Why did Hubble's straight line show that the universe had a beginning?

answer: Because the line meant the universe is expanding, and an expanding universe must have been smaller in the past.
consequence: Exactly. Running the expansion backward takes you to a single starting point where everything began.

answer: Because redshift proves that light gets tired as it travels.
consequence: This idea was proposed in the early 20th century. It does not hold up against other evidence such as the cosmic microwave background.

answer: Because farther galaxies emit red light for chemical reasons.
consequence: The galaxies are not chemically redder. Their spectral lines are shifted as a whole toward the red end. The elements are the same, only the motion differs.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: A universe expanding today must have been smaller yesterday. At some point it was small enough that the word "universe" meant something very different. That starting point is what we call the Big Bang.
hint: If everything is moving apart now, what was the arrangement long ago.

@text
The idea Hubble's line pointed at became known as the <c:g>Big Bang</c:g>.
This idea reshaped how physics thinks about time.
For him, it was the moment physics stopped treating the universe as a fixed background.
From then on, the universe had a beginning, a middle, and a direction.
That is a strange thing to say about the whole of existence.
But the strangeness came from measurement, not imagination.

@true_false
The Big Bang was a single explosion that happened at one specific place in the existing universe.

true: True, it was an explosion in space.
consequence: "Bang" suggests an explosion, but that picture is wrong. The Big Bang is the expansion of space itself, happening everywhere at once. There was no "outside."

false: False, space itself was expanding, not exploding into something.
consequence: Right. There is no center and no edge. Every point is moving away from every other point.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The Big Bang is the expansion of space itself, not an event within an existing space. The word "bang" misleads more often than it helps.
hint: Ask where the Big Bang happened, and notice that the honest answer is "everywhere."

@reflect
A pattern you noticed in your own life but never followed up on: your best work always happening at the same time of day.
An answer to a big question that turned out to be surprisingly ordinary: "because I finally slept well."
A moment when data told you something your instinct disagreed with: an experiment result that did not match your guess.
